I was recently talking to someone who was having trouble with understanding the performance of this function (yes this could theoretically be optimized to a memset):
```rust
pub fn build(weights: &[u32]) -> Vec<u32> {
    let mut cdf = Vec::with_capacity(weights.len() + 1);
    unsafe {
        *cdf.get_unchecked_mut(0) = 0;
    }

    for (i, weight) in weights.iter().enumerate() {
        unsafe {
            *cdf.get_unchecked_mut(i + 1) = cdf.get_unchecked(i) + *weight;
        }
    }

    unsafe {
        cdf.set_len(weights.len() + 1);
    }

    cdf
}
```
I eventually narrowed this down to some kind of instability related to codegen of the inner loop. With the default release profile I see this in `perf annotate`:
```
       │b0:┌─→add    (%r14,%rsi,1),%edx
 34.95 │   │  mov    %edx,0x4(%rax,%rsi,1)
 65.05 │   │  add    $0x4,%rsi
       │   ├──cmp    %rsi,%rbx
       │   └──jne    b0
```
Which seems fine. But then another person (trying to be helpful) suggests turning on LTO and the inner loop now becomes this:
```
       │b0:┌─→add  (%rbx),%edx
 36.45 │   │  add  $0x4,%rbx
  0.77 │   │  mov  %edx,(%rcx)
 61.32 │   │  add  $0x4,%rcx
  0.29 │   ├──cmp  %rax,%rbx
  1.17 │   └──jne  b0
```
Which benchmarks significantly slower.


